summary: Popular Locations Wednesday Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County L.A.'s Natural History Museum if the largest museum of...
caption:
Popular Locations Wednesday

Natural History Museum of Los Angeles County

L.A.’s Natural History Museum if the largest museum of its type on the west coast containing over 35 million artifacts and specimens including an extensive research collection. The museum opened in 1913 designed in the Beaux Arts style and was expanded over the years in a variety of different styles including Neoclassical, Romanesque, and Spanish Plateresque.

The museum can be seen above as the Jeffersonian Institute in Bones, the starting point of a race in MacGyver, a museum in Buffy the Vampire Slayer, and a spider research lab in Spider-Man.

It can also be found in Alias, Charmed, Pretty Woman, The Monster Squad, 90210, Escape from the Planet of the Apes, and more.

title: IRON MAN 2
body:
Holy balls, this movie. Iron Man 2 is like if Tony Stark’s ego became sentient and turned itself into digital code. Like Ultron! Just like Ultron! Shiny, curvy, childish and full of itself! One of Marvel’s greatest strengths is to trust its creatives: the biggest property in the world right now is in the hands of two guys who directed the paintball episode of Community, while Black Panther has Ryan Coogler’s signature all over it, especially in the genius contrast of Wakanda with Compton. But initially this trust resulted in a self-indulgent clusterfuck that could have sunk the whole thing if Cap and Thor hadn’t whizzed in to pick up the pieces. Iron Man 2 seems to be the result of Downey Jr. and Jon Favreau being given a big blank cheque as long as they shoehorn Black Widow and Nick Fury in and mumble something about the Avengers. At the time it was a massive, dickabout disappointment, but after twenty something actual serious movies that deliver on the premise of its predecessors’s sting it’s actually kind of fun.

 A kind of fun selection of moments rather than a movie. Garry Shandling saying ‘Fuck you Mr Stark.’ Iron Man getting drunk and DJing. Mickey Rourke escaping from prison, car alarms going off on a fly past, the sheer wankabout opulence of the fantastic Grand Prix sequence. Robert Downey Jr saying the words ‘Give me a fat beat to beat my buddy’s ass to’. But that’s all they are, moments. There is so much filler, ad-libbing and dicking about here that the movie somehow lasts for two hours and still has no time to develop its antagonists or provide more action than two brief sections dotted amongst the endless chatter. In the same way that Guardians 2 would become a bloated mess that loved its protagonists way too much nearly ten years later Tony Stark is a black hole here, sucking in plot, pacing, suspense, story and all the other characters until there’s only his beard left, and his bigger weirder hair, and his shit eating grin. It’s all about an expo! An expo all about him!

 And yet… and yet, through sheer force of will, it’s still kind of entertaining. Downey Jr might be stuffed into every frame but he’s still adorable. The last half hour is great. The last half-hours are always great in sub-par Marvels. The intros of Black Widow and War Machine action are just about enough to sate those chomping at the bit for the Avengers and in the context of the wider MCU the whole thing fares even better, a chill out sesh before shit really kicks off, the Monaco scenes in particular a perfect money-fest sixties fuckabout. It’s goofing off with a bigger budget, and all that money’s up there on screen, but in ways it never would be again. It absolutely does not feel like a ‘superhero’ film, and that makes it kind of work, as a curio of the genre and a portrait of an important character cutting loose before they really gave him some growth later on. And they ret-conned in Spider-Man too, which works amazingly well considering what came later.

 Somehow a loose slog of surface devouring structure, it’s the polar opposite of the tight, formal brilliance of Iron Man Three, which everyone hates for some reason. They’re wrong. Iron Man 2 meanwhile is definitely one of the worst Marvel movies, which is a sign of how good they are.
